Abstract

This thesis develops a comprehensive mathematical framework for understanding non-equilibrium quantum vacuum interactions under multi-scale boundary conditions. While the static Casimir effect is well-understood within Quantum Electrodynamics (QED), the regime of simultaneously applied mechanical, electromagnetic, and topological modulations remains largely unexplored theoretically. We derive a generalized path integral formulation for the effective action of the electromagnetic field in cavities with time-dependent boundary conditions and non-trivial spacetime metrics. The research establishes rigorous mathematical connections between the Dynamical Casimir Effect (DCE), Floquet engineering in superconducting circuits, and the generation of spacetime metric perturbations from vacuum energy gradients. By constructing a unified theoretical architecture based on quantum field theory in curved spacetime and non-commutative geometry, we derive testable predictions for vacuum friction, photon pair production spectra, and the possibility of vacuum-engineered stress-energy tensors. The primary contribution is a complete mathematical taxonomy of vacuum states under multi-modal driving, providing the theoretical foundation for future experimental programs while rigorously addressing questions of energy conservation, causality, and the limits of vacuum manipulation.

