9. Mathematical Derivations (Selected Examples)

9.1 Derivation of Mode Coupling Matrices

We derive $A_{nm}(t)$ explicitly. Start with orthonormality:

\int_{\Omega(t)} d^3x \, u_n(x;t) u_m(x;t) = \delta_{nm}

Take time derivative:

\int_{\Omega(t)} d^3x \, [\dot{u}_n u_m + u_n \dot{u}_m] + \int_{\partial\Omega(t)} d^2\sigma \, (\mathbf{v}\cdot\hat{n}) u_n u_m = 0

Where $\mathbf{v}$ is boundary velocity. This yields a relation for the matrix elements of $\dot{u}$.

For Dirichlet boundaries, $u_n|_{\partial\Omega} = 0$, so the boundary term vanishes. Then:

\int d^3x \, \dot{u}_n u_m = -\int d^3x \, u_n \dot{u}_m

Thus $A_{nm}(t) = 2\int d^3x \, u_n \dot{u}_m$ is antisymmetric: $A_{nm} = -A_{mn}$.

9.2 Bogoliubov Coefficients for Two-Frequency Driving

For a single mode coupled to itself (parametric amplification), the equation of motion is:

\ddot{q} + \omega_0^2[1 + \epsilon_1\sin(\omega_1 t) + \epsilon_2\sin(\omega_2 t)]^2 q = 0

To first order in $\epsilon$, this becomes a Mathieu-type equation with two frequencies. Using the method of multiple scales, we seek solutions of the form:

q(t) = A_1(T_1, T_2) e^{i\omega_0 t} + A_2(T_1, T_2) e^{-i\omega_0 t} + \text{c.c.}

Where $T_1 = \epsilon t$, $T_2 = \epsilon^2 t$ are slow times. Substituting and eliminating secular terms yields coupled amplitude equations whose solution gives the Bogoliubov coefficients.

9.3 Stress-Energy Tensor Renormalization

The vacuum expectation value $\langle T_{\mu\nu} \rangle$ diverges and must be renormalized. For a static cavity, we use point-splitting regularization:

\langle T_{\mu\nu} \rangle = \lim_{x'\to x} \mathcal{D}_{\mu\nu} [G(x,x') - G_0(x,x')]

Where $G$ is the Feynman propagator in the cavity and $G_0$ is the Minkowski space propagator. $\mathcal{D}_{\mu\nu}$ is a differential operator obtained from the classical stress tensor.

For time-dependent cavities, this becomes:

\langle T_{\mu\nu}(x) \rangle = \lim_{x'\to x} \mathcal{D}_{\mu\nu} [G(x,x') - G_{\text{ad}}(x,x')]

Where $G_{\text{ad}}$ is an adiabatic propagator that subtracts the local divergences while preserving the physical time-dependence.

